u2010 and photoperiod\u2010dependent.\n                \n                \n                  We further used the model to predict survival probabilities at five locations across a latitudinal gradient (60.1\u00b0\u2009N to 70.9\u00b0\u2009N), finding that combinations of photoperiod and temperature conditions limited population distributions in the model.\n                \n                \n                  \n                    To verify our model results, we compared predictions for optimal decisions with our own empirical data collected on northern bats (\n                    Eptesicus nilssonii\n                    ) from two latitudes in Norway. The similarities between our predictions and observations provide strong evidence that this model framework incorporates the most important drivers of diurnal decision\u2010making in bat physiology and behaviour.\n                  \n                \n                \n                  Comparing empirical data and model predictions also revealed that bats facing lighter night conditions further north restrict their mass gain, which strengthens the hypothesis that predation threat is a main driver of bat nocturnality. Our model findings regarding state\u2010dependent decisions in bats should contribute to the understanding of how bats cope with the summer challenges at high latitudes.", "access_right": "restricted", "creators": [{"name": "Fjelldal, Mari Aas", "affiliation": null}, {"name": "Muller, Amandine Sophie", "affiliation": null}, {"name": "Ratikainen, Irja Ida", "affiliation": null}, {"name": "Stawski, Clare", "affiliation": null}, {"name": "Wright, Jonathan", "affiliation": null}], "keywords": ["Biodiversity", "Mammalia", "Chiroptera", "Chordata", "Animalia", "bats", "bat"], "related_identifiers": [{"identifier": "hash://md5/26901e82417143514d1e3c49627cbfd3", "relation": "hasVersion", "scheme": "url"}, {"identifier": "hash://sha256/65e7c7ab47129c5e9903be16c0ae2ce9a46b6b0fb10fc2b9a586650a74ea0607", "relation":